---

<Canvas title="10 · Settlement &amp; Chains — Sardis Canvas" currentId="settlement">
<Fragment slot="head">
  <style is:global set:html={styles}></style>
</Fragment>

<section class="hero">
        <span class="eyebrow">Canvas 10 · Flows</span>
        <h1>Settlement &amp; Chains</h1>
        <p class="hero-lead">
          Once a transaction is policy-approved and signed, it has to actually move money — and money
          moves on many different rails. Sardis supports six EVM chains, Tempo, Circle's Arc, and fiat
          off-ramps through Stripe, Striga, and Bridge. This canvas walks the rail map, the cross-chain
          path via CCTP, and the reconciliation machinery that keeps it all honest.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="section" style="padding-top:0; border-top:0;">
        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <span class="callout-title">TL;DR</span>
          Chains are defined in <code>ChainConfig</code>
          (<code>packages/sardis-core/src/sardis_v2_core/config.py</code>); token contracts live in
          <code>tokens.py</code>. <code>ChainExecutor</code> in
          <code>packages/sardis-chain/src/sardis_chain/executor.py</code> owns submission; CCTP v2 handles
          cross-chain USDC; Stripe / Striga / Bridge handle fiat off-ramp. Settlement state is explicit
          (migration 048), provider-rail is tracked (053), and a persistent reconciliation queue (057)
          catches anything that falls off.
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Supported chains -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Rails</div>
          <h2>Supported chains — the authoritative list.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:760px;">
            The mainnets below are defined directly in <code>ChainConfig</code>. Any chain with a token
            contract in <code>tokens.py</code> can be added to that list with a single entry — no executor
            changes needed for EVM-family networks.
          </p>
        </div>
        <table class="data">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Chain</th><th>Chain ID</th><th>RPC default</th><th>Tokens</th><th>Status</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Base</td><td>8453</td><td><code>https://mainnet.base.org</code> (Alchemy in prod via <code>SARDIS_BASE_RPC_URL</code>)</td><td>USDC, EURC</td><td><span class="badge badge-success">mainnet</span> primary</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Tempo</td><td>4217</td><td><code>https://rpc.tempo.xyz</code></td><td>USDC (pathUSD), USDC.e, EURC</td><td><span class="badge badge-success">mainnet</span> live since 2026-03-18</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Ethereum</td><td>1</td><td>Alchemy</td><td>USDC, USDT, PYUSD, EURC</td><td>mainnet (token addresses configured)</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Polygon</td><td>137</td><td>Alchemy</td><td>USDC, USDT, EURC</td><td>mainnet</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Arbitrum</td><td>42161</td><td>Alchemy</td><td>USDC, USDT</td><td>mainnet</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Optimism</td><td>10</td><td>Alchemy</td><td>USDC, USDT</td><td>mainnet</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Solana</td><td>—</td><td>Solana RPC</td><td>USDC, USDT, PYUSD</td><td>tokens configured; separate executor under <code>sardis_chain/solana/</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td>Morph</td><td>—</td><td>Public RPC</td><td>USDC</td><td>token configured</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Base Sepolia</td><td>84532</td><td><code>https://sepolia.base.org</code></td><td>USDC</td><td><span class="badge">testnet</span></td></tr>
            <tr><td>Tempo Testnet (Moderato)</td><td>42429</td><td><code>https://rpc.testnet.tempo.xyz</code></td><td>USDC (pathUSD), EURC</td><td><span class="badge">testnet</span></td></tr>
            <tr><td>Arc Testnet</td><td>~421614 (confirm w/ docs)</td><td><code>https://rpc.testnet.arc.network</code></td><td>USDC, EURC</td><td><span class="badge">testnet</span> Circle USDC-native L1</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <!-- Tokens -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Tokens</div>
          <h2>The token registry.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:760px;">
            <code>TokenType</code> enum + <code>TOKEN_REGISTRY</code> in
            <code>tokens.py</code>. Each token carries decimals, issuer, peg metadata, and a
            <code>contract_addresses: dict[chain, address]</code>. A token is considered "supported on a
            chain" iff the chain key exists in that dict.
          </p>
        </div>
        <table class="data">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Token</th><th>Decimals</th><th>Issuer</th><th>Peg</th><th>Chains with contract configured</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>USDC</td><td>6</td><td>Circle</td><td>USD</td><td>base, ethereum, polygon, arbitrum, optimism, solana, base_sepolia, arc_testnet, tempo (pathUSD), tempo_testnet, morph</td></tr>
            <tr><td>USDC.e (bridged, TIP-20)</td><td>6</td><td>Circle (bridged)</td><td>USD</td><td>tempo</td></tr>
            <tr><td>USDT</td><td>6</td><td>Tether</td><td>USD</td><td>ethereum, polygon, arbitrum, optimism, solana</td></tr>
            <tr><td>PYUSD</td><td>6</td><td>PayPal</td><td>USD</td><td>ethereum, solana</td></tr>
            <tr><td>EURC</td><td>6</td><td>Circle</td><td>EUR (1.08)</td><td>base, ethereum, polygon, arc_testnet, tempo, tempo_testnet</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <div class="callout mt-16">
          <span class="callout-title">TIP-20 note</span>
          On Tempo, bridged USDC uses a TIP-20 <code>transferWithMemo</code> ABI — see the
          <code>is_tip20</code> flag on <code>TokenMetadata</code>. The Tempo executor branches on this;
          other chains use the standard ERC-20 ABI.
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Base primary -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Base</div>
          <h2>The primary production rail.</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="grid grid-2">
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Why Base is default</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              Coinbase-native L2, Circle Paymaster v0.8 works permissionlessly with no API key, sub-cent
              fees, mature bundler ecosystem (Pimlico + Alchemy), Safe v1.4.1 singleton pre-deployed.
              For USDC-denominated agent flows, Base is the path of least resistance.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">RPC strategy</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              Alchemy primary via <code>SARDIS_BASE_RPC_URL</code>, public <code>mainnet.base.org</code>
              as fallback. <code>ChainRPCClient</code> in <code>executor.py</code> handles retries and
              failover between endpoints.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Checkout default</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              <code>SARDIS_CHECKOUT_CHAIN</code> defaults to <code>base</code>. "Pay with Sardis" resolves
              to a Base USDC transfer unless the merchant explicitly opts into another rail.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Smart contracts here</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              <code>SardisLedgerAnchor.sol</code>, ERC-8183 stack, reference Safe modules — all intended
              first for Base mainnet (and mirrored to Tempo). See canvas 06 · Contracts.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Tempo deep dive -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Tempo</div>
          <h2>Why Tempo got first-class status.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:760px;">
            Tempo launched mainnet on 2026-03-18 alongside Stripe's MPP (Merchant Payment Protocol) — we
            shipped Sardis live on it on day one. It's not just another EVM chain; it's payments-native.
          </p>
        </div>
        <dl class="defs">
          <dt>Chain</dt><dd>chain_id 4217, RPC <code>https://rpc.tempo.xyz</code></dd>
          <dt>Architecture</dt><dd>100K+ TPS target; EVM-compatible execution; Keychain precompile for agent permissions; fee-payer abstraction for gas-in-USDC.</dd>
          <dt>Ownership</dt><dd>Matt Huang (Paradigm) CEO, $500M Series A at $5B valuation.</dd>
          <dt>Dedicated executor</dt><dd><code>packages/sardis-chain/src/sardis_chain/tempo/executor.py</code> (not shared with EVM executor — TIP-20 ABI + keychain sigs + fee-payer flow).</dd>
          <dt>Keychain</dt><dd><code>packages/sardis-wallet/src/sardis_wallet/tempo_keychain.py</code> — maps Sardis policy to on-chain Access Keys. See canvas 09.</dd>
          <dt>Fee payer</dt><dd><code>tempo/fee_payer.py</code> — native gas-abstraction support, no separate paymaster.</dd>
          <dt>Tokens</dt><dd>pathUSD (USDC) at <code>0x20c0000000000000000000000000000000000000</code>; USDC.e (bridged) at <code>0x20C000000000000000000000b9537d11c60E8b50</code>; EURC at <code>0x20c0000000000000000000001621e21f71cf12fb</code>.</dd>
          <dt>DEX integration</dt><dd><code>tempo/dex.py</code> — native DEX for on-chain swaps when cross-currency flows stay on Tempo.</dd>
        </dl>
      </section>

      <!-- CCTP v2 -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Cross-chain</div>
          <h2>CCTP v2 — USDC across chains without bridges.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:760px;">
            Circle Cross-Chain Transfer Protocol v2: burn USDC on source, mint USDC on destination. No
            wrapped assets, no pooled liquidity, no bridge counterparty risk. Sardis uses it wherever a
            payment starts on one chain and settles on another.
          </p>
        </div>
        <dl class="defs">
          <dt>Implementation</dt><dd><code>packages/sardis-chain/src/sardis_chain/cctp.py</code> — <code>CCTPBridgeService</code>, <code>BridgeTransfer</code>, <code>BridgeStatus</code></dd>
          <dt>Constants</dt><dd><code>cctp_constants.py</code> — domain IDs, TokenMessenger / MessageTransmitter addresses per chain</dd>
          <dt>Forwarding helper</dt><dd><code>cctp_forwarding.py</code> — destination-chain forwarding so the minted USDC lands where the agent actually wants it, not at the messenger address</dd>
          <dt>Unified addresses</dt><dd>CCTP v2's big win — same token messenger address on every chain, so integrations aren't n² chain pairs.</dd>
          <dt>Typical use</dt><dd>Agent holds USDC on Base; merchant is on Polygon; <code>CCTPBridgeService.bridge_usdc()</code> burns on Base, mints on Polygon, forwards to merchant address in one flow.</dd>
        </dl>
        <div class="diagram">
          <pre class="mermaid" is:raw>
sequenceDiagram
    participant A as Agent (Base)
    participant Ex as ChainExecutor
    participant TMb as TokenMessenger (Base)
    participant Attest as Circle Attestation
    participant TMp as MessageTransmitter (Polygon)
    participant M as Merchant (Polygon)

    A->>Ex: bridge_usdc(amount, to=Polygon, recipient=M)
    Ex->>TMb: depositForBurnWithCaller(amount, domain=polygon, ...)
    TMb-->>Ex: burn event + message hash
    Ex->>Attest: poll attestation for message
    Attest-->>Ex: signed attestation
    Ex->>TMp: receiveMessage(message, attestation)
    TMp->>M: mint USDC → recipient
    Ex-->>A: BridgeStatus.COMPLETED, dst tx hash
          </pre>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Fiat off-ramps -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Fiat off-ramps</div>
          <h2>USDC → merchant bank, three providers.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:760px;">
            Merchants eventually want fiat in their bank account. Sardis doesn't pick one provider — it
            picks the cheapest path per currency and region. The selector lives in
            <code>CrossCurrencySettlementService</code>.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="grid grid-3">
          <div class="rail-card">
            <div class="rail-label">Stripe Connect</div>
            <div class="rail-title">US / USD · ACH</div>
            <p class="text-sm text-muted">USDC → USD → merchant bank. Connected Account model; Sardis handles the conversion and Stripe handles the ACH settlement.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="rail-card">
            <div class="rail-label">Striga</div>
            <div class="rail-title">EU / EUR · SEPA + vIBANs</div>
            <p class="text-sm text-muted">EURC → EUR → SEPA. Per-merchant vIBANs so inbound SEPA lands against a known merchant identity. Fee ~0.3%.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="rail-card">
            <div class="rail-label">Bridge</div>
            <div class="rail-title">Multi-rail · ACH / SEPA / PIX / Wire</div>
            <p class="text-sm text-muted">Provider abstraction over bank-settlement rails worldwide. Fee ~0.5% on USDC → USD. Used when Stripe / Striga don't cover the geography.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h3 class="mt-32">Path selection</h3>
        <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:760px;">
          <code>CrossCurrencySettlementService.get_settlement_quotes()</code> enumerates viable paths per
          request, scores by total fee + estimated time, and returns quotes. <code>select_optimal_path()</code>
          picks the best. The path identifiers are stable: <code>usdc_bridge_usd</code>,
          <code>usdc_grid_fx_eur</code>, <code>eurc_striga_eur</code>, <code>direct_stablecoin</code>.
        </p>
        <div class="diagram">
          <pre class="mermaid" is:raw>
flowchart LR
    P[Payment settles in USDC] --> Q{Merchant currency?}
    Q -- USD (US) --> S1[Stripe Connect: USDC → USD → ACH]
    Q -- EUR (EU) --> S2[Striga: EURC → EUR → SEPA]
    Q -- EUR (fallback) --> S3[Bridge: USDC → Grid FX → EUR → SEPA]
    Q -- BRL --> S4[Bridge: USDC → PIX]
    Q -- USD (non-Stripe) --> S5[Bridge: USDC → ACH/Wire]
    Q -- Stablecoin --> S6[Direct: stablecoin-to-stablecoin, no FX]
          </pre>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- FX -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">FX</div>
          <h2>Quotes and cross-currency settlement.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:760px;">
            When source and destination currency differ, a quote has to be recorded: the rate, the fee
            breakdown, the expected received amount. That quote is part of the payment's evidence record —
            disputes reference it directly.
          </p>
        </div>
        <dl class="defs">
          <dt>Service</dt><dd><code>packages/sardis-core/src/sardis_v2_core/cross_currency_settlement.py</code> — <code>CrossCurrencySettlementService</code></dd>
          <dt>Quote type</dt><dd><code>SettlementQuote</code>: path, source &amp; target currency/amount, exchange_rate, total_fee_cents, fee_breakdown, estimated_time_seconds, <code>fee_percent</code> property</dd>
          <dt>Result type</dt><dd><code>SettlementResult</code>: settlement_id, path, amounts, status, <code>provider_tx_ids[]</code>, metadata</dd>
          <dt>FX helpers</dt><dd><code>fx_quote.py</code> (quote construction), <code>fx_signer.py</code> in <code>sardis-chain</code> (chain-side FX signing), Grid FX + Circle Cross-Currency adapters (<code>circle_cross_currency.py</code>).</dd>
          <dt>Fee defaults (bps)</dt><dd>Bridge 50, Grid FX 50, Striga swap 30. Configurable at service init.</dd>
        </dl>
      </section>

      <!-- Settlement tracking -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Tracking</div>
          <h2>Settlement is explicit, not best-effort.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:760px;">
            "Payment succeeded" has two meanings: the chain accepted the tx, and the merchant's money
            actually arrived. The <code>settlement_records</code> table captures the full lifecycle of the
            second one.
          </p>
        </div>
        <dl class="defs">
          <dt>Migration</dt><dd><code>packages/sardis-api/migrations/048_settlement_tracking.sql</code></dd>
          <dt>Table</dt><dd><code>settlement_records</code></dd>
          <dt>Key fields</dt><dd><code>settlement_id</code> (unique), <code>intent_id</code>, <code>receipt_id</code>, <code>mode</code>, <code>status</code>, <code>amount</code>, <code>currency</code>, <code>fee</code>, <code>network_reference</code>, <code>credential_id</code></dd>
          <dt>Card-path fields</dt><dd><code>authorization_status</code>, <code>capture_status</code>, <code>dispute_status</code>, <code>reversal_reference</code>, <code>liability_party</code></dd>
          <dt>Timeline</dt><dd><code>initiated_at</code> → <code>confirmed_at</code> → <code>settled_at</code> (or <code>failed_at</code>). <code>expected_settlement_at</code> powers the "stuck settlements" alert.</dd>
          <dt>Indexes</dt><dd><code>idx_stl_intent</code>, <code>idx_stl_status(status, mode)</code>, partial <code>idx_stl_pending</code> (initiated/pending_confirmation only), partial <code>idx_stl_disputes</code>.</dd>
        </dl>
      </section>

      <!-- Provider rail -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Provider rail</div>
          <h2>Which rail actually processed a payment.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:760px;">
            The same logical payment can ride different provider rails depending on routing. Operators
            need to see which one in every row — for reconciliation, cost analysis, and incident response.
          </p>
        </div>
        <dl class="defs">
          <dt>Migration</dt><dd><code>packages/sardis-api/migrations/053_provider_rail_tracking.sql</code></dd>
          <dt>Columns on <code>transactions</code></dt><dd><code>provider_rail VARCHAR(50)</code>, <code>provider_payment_reference VARCHAR(255)</code></dd>
          <dt>Valid values</dt><dd><code>stripe_spt</code>, <code>visa_tap</code>, <code>mastercard_agent_pay</code>, <code>circle_cpn</code>, <code>bridge_ach</code>, <code>bridge_sepa</code>, <code>bridge_pix</code></dd>
          <dt>Index</dt><dd><code>idx_transactions_provider(provider_rail, created_at)</code> — powers the "costs by rail this month" dashboard query.</dd>
          <dt>Why it matters</dt><dd>When a provider has an incident, operators need a one-query answer to "which payments are currently on that rail?" — without this column, you're grepping JSON metadata at 3am.</dd>
        </dl>
      </section>

      <!-- Reconciliation -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Reconciliation</div>
          <h2>Persistent queue — because chains reorg and RPCs flake.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:760px;">
            If the on-chain tx lands but the ledger append fails, we can't just forget about it. The
            reconciliation queue holds the half-written payment until the ledger append succeeds.
            Persistence means a process restart doesn't lose a cent.
          </p>
        </div>
        <dl class="defs">
          <dt>Migration</dt><dd><code>packages/sardis-api/migrations/057_reconciliation_queue.sql</code></dd>
          <dt>Table</dt><dd><code>reconciliation_queue</code></dd>
          <dt>Schema</dt><dd><code>entry_type TEXT</code>, <code>payload_json JSONB</code>, <code>status</code> (pending / processing / resolved / failed), <code>retry_count</code>, <code>created_at</code>, <code>processed_at</code></dd>
          <dt>Index</dt><dd>Partial <code>idx_recon_queue_status</code> WHERE status='pending' — the worker only ever scans pending rows.</dd>
          <dt>Why it exists</dt><dd>Replaces a prior <code>InMemoryReconciliationQueue</code> that lost entries on restart. Any payment where ledger append fails after chain execution now persists its reconciliation state across process restarts.</dd>
          <dt>Operator behavior</dt><dd>Alert fires when <code>retry_count &gt; N</code> or <code>status = 'failed'</code>. Human-in-the-loop resolution.</dd>
        </dl>
      </section>

      <!-- Adjacent services -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Supporting services</div>
          <h2>Executor-adjacent modules worth naming.</h2>
        </div>
        <table class="data">
          <thead><tr><th>File</th><th>Role</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><code>sardis_chain/executor.py</code></td><td><code>ChainExecutor</code>, <code>ChainRPCClient</code>, <code>SubmittedTx</code>, <code>GasEstimate</code>, <code>GasPriceProtection</code>, <code>TransactionRequest</code>.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>sardis_chain/nonce_manager.py</code> / <code>redis_nonce_manager.py</code></td><td>Per-wallet nonce coordination — Redis-backed in prod to survive concurrent submissions.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>sardis_chain/gas_optimizer.py</code></td><td>Gas pricing + spike protection (via <code>GasPriceProtection</code>).</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>sardis_chain/mev_protection.py</code></td><td>Private transaction submission where available — Flashbots-style for flows where MEV risk is real.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>sardis_chain/confirmation.py</code></td><td>Receipt polling, reorg handling.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>sardis_chain/permit2.py</code></td><td>Uniswap Permit2 for gasless approvals where relevant.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>sardis_chain/cdp_swap.py</code></td><td>Coinbase CDP swap service integration.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>sardis_chain/liquidity_router.py</code></td><td>Routing for cross-venue swap execution.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>sardis_chain/simulation.py</code></td><td>Pre-flight tx simulation — catch reverts before broadcast.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>sardis_chain/provider_tracker.py</code></td><td>Records provider rail choice → feeds the <code>provider_rail</code> column in migration 053.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>sardis_chain/deposit_monitor.py</code></td><td>Watches deposit addresses for inbound USDC (checkout funding detection).</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>sardis_chain/bridges/</code> + <code>bridge.py</code> + <code>bridge_xyz.py</code></td><td>Bridge provider adapters (Bridge.xyz etc.) alongside CCTP.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>sardis-core/fiat_orchestrator.py</code></td><td>Orchestrates the USDC → fiat handoff (Stripe / Striga / Bridge path selection).</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <!-- Cross-refs -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Go deeper</div>
          <h2>Follow-ups.</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="grid grid-2">
          <a class="canvas-card" href="/wallet-mpc">
            <div class="canvas-card-num">09 · Flows</div>
            <div class="canvas-card-title">Wallet + MPC</div>
            <div class="canvas-card-desc">What produces the signed tx that the executor broadcasts.</div>
          </a>
          <a class="canvas-card" href="/policy-engine">
            <div class="canvas-card-num">08 · Flows</div>
            <div class="canvas-card-title">Policy Engine</div>
            <div class="canvas-card-desc">Chain/token allowlists that gate what rails a policy can use.</div>
          </a>
          <a class="canvas-card" href="/database">
            <div class="canvas-card-num">05 · Backend</div>
            <div class="canvas-card-title">Database Schema</div>
            <div class="canvas-card-desc">Migrations 048, 053, 057 in context.</div>
